General Social Survey¶

Essential variables exploration¶

This notebook look at the General Social Survey (GSS), exploring essential variables in the over the 50+ years of survey data. The primary data file for this exploration (gss7221_r j2.dta) can be found in the GSS Strata archive. If you want to work with this data for your own analysis, it is also essential to review the survey codebooks.

Special thanks to Allen Downey for all the work they have published on crafting jupyter notebooks with GSS data.

This notebook is part of the GeneralSocialSurvey github repository.

Seaborn is the plotting library used to generate these visualizations.

This variable tracks responses to the following question:




Last week were you working full time, part time, going to schoool, keeping house, or what?

t = "Last week were you working full time, part time, going to schoool, keeping house, or what?"

spaced_labels = ['',
          'Working full time',
          'Working part time',
          'Temp Unemployed',
          'Unemployed',
          'Retired',
          'In school', 
          'Keeping House', 
          'Other', 
          '']

labels = filter(lambda label: label != '', spaced_labels)

p = sns.displot(
    data=gss, 
    kind="hist",
    x="wrkstat",
    multiple="stack", 
    discrete=True, 
    height=4,
    aspect=2, 
    legend=False,
    shrink=.95,
    stat="density", 
    common_norm=False
)
p.set_xticklabels(spaced_labels)
p.set_xlabels(t)
plt.xticks(rotation=25)
plt.draw()
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")


h = sns.catplot(
    data=gss, 
    x="wrkstat", 
    y="age", 
    palette='tab10',
    kind="boxen",
    height=6,
    aspect=2, 
)

h.set_xticklabels(labels)
h.set_xlabels(t)
h.set_ylabels('participant age')
plt.draw()

Variable: sex¶
Notes: Prior to 2021, SEX was interviewer coded. In 2021, SEX is a composite of SEXBIRTH1 and SEXNOW1 See GSS Methodological Report No. 9.


If planning to perform trend analysis with this variable, please consult GSS Methodological Report No. 56.



















In [8]:



     


t = "birth sex"

p = sns.displot(
    data=gss, 
    kind="hist",
    x="sex",
    multiple="stack", 
    discrete=True, 
    height=4,
    aspect=2, 
    legend=False,
    shrink=.95,
    stat="density", 
    common_norm=False
)
plt.xticks(range(4))
p.set_xticklabels(['', 'male', 'female', ''])
p.set_xlabels(t)
plt.draw()
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")


h = sns.catplot(
    data=gss, 
    x="sex", 
    y="age", 
    palette='tab10',
    kind="boxen",
    height=6,
    aspect=2, 
)

h.set_xlabels(t)
h.set_ylabels('participant age')
h.set_xticklabels(['male', 'female'])
plt.draw()


by_year = sns.displot(
    gss, 
    x="year", 
    hue="sex", 
    palette='tab10',
    kind="kde",

    aspect=2,
    legend=False,
)

GSS Question/Variable: Health¶
Would you say your own health, in general, is excellent, good, fair, or poor?



















In [12]:



     


labels = ['',
'Excellent',
'Good',
'Fair',
'Poor']


t = "Would you say your own health, in general, is excellent, good, fair, or poor?"

p = sns.displot(
    data=gss, 
    kind="hist",
    x="health",
    discrete=True, 
    height=5,
    aspect=2, 
    legend=False,
    shrink=.95,
    stat="density", 
    common_norm=False
)
plt.xticks(range(5))
p.set_xlabels(t)
p.set_xticklabels(labels)
plt.draw()
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")

labels2 = filter(lambda label: label != '', labels)


h = sns.catplot(
    data=gss, 
    x="health", 
    y="age", 
    palette='tab10',
    kind="boxen",
    height=6,
    aspect=2, 
)

h.set_xlabels(t)
h.set_ylabels('participant age')
h.set_xticklabels(labels2)
plt.draw()

i = sns.catplot(
    data=gss, 
    x="health", 
    y="income", 
    palette='tab10',
    kind="boxen",
    height=6,
    aspect=2, 
)

labels3 = filter(lambda label: label != '', labels)

i.set_xlabels(t)
i.set_ylabels('participant income bracket')
i.set_xticklabels(labels3)
plt.draw()


by_year = sns.displot(
    gss, 
    x="year", 
    hue="health", 
    palette='pastel',
    kind="kde",
    height=6,
    aspect=2,
    legend=False,
)


plt.legend(title='Health', labels=labels, loc = 2, bbox_to_anchor = (1,1))
plt.draw()
